<hr /></div>

<div id="main-text">

<h2 id="FundTextApprIssu">1. The Fundamental Texts, the Approaches, the Issues</h2>

<p>
The above considerations show that the fate of metaphysics as a branch
of philosophy in the Arabic speaking world and in Muslim societies
coincides, by and large, with the reception and transformation of
Aristotle&rsquo;s <em>Metaphysics</em>. The anti-Aristotelian
tendencies of the early phase of Arabic philosophy, marked by the
adoption of a decidedly Platonic stance in metaphysics and the
consequent rejection of Aristotle&rsquo;s teaching, evident in the
views of Ab&#363; Bakr Mu&#7717;ammad ibn Zakariy&#257;&#702;
al-R&#257;z&#299; (d. ca. 925), remained a local and short-lived
phenomenon. In mainstream Arabic philosophy, the <em>Metaphysics</em>
represented for centuries the centerpiece of the corresponding
discipline. Aristotle&rsquo;s work is the prime, and very often the
only, Greek work mentioned in connection with metaphysics in the the
classifications of the sciences devised in <em>falsafa</em>. No other
Greek metaphysical work was translated and commented upon in the same
continuous, widespread, and multiform manner, or quoted so often and
extensively used. The variety of titles which Aristotle&rsquo;s work
received in the Arabic tradition, by means of transliterations of the
Greek title, translations of it, and more original denominations (like
&ldquo;Book of Letters&rdquo;), and the corresponding multifarious
ways of referring to the science contained therein, are clear sign of
the far-reaching and impactful dissemination of the
<em>Metaphysics</em> in Arabic. Other vehicles of Greek metaphysical
thought, like the <em>Theologia Aristotelis</em>, whose aim was to
make Aristotle&rsquo;s work compatible with Islamic creationism by
means of the Neoplatonic doctrine of emanation, stress from the outset
the primacy of the <em>Metaphysics</em> as the fundamental text of
metaphysics, and fictively portray Aristotle as the author of the
adaptation of the Plotinian material by means of which the desired
completion of the <em>Metaphysics</em> is performed. If the
<em>Metaphysics</em>&mdash;as well as the entire Aristotelian
<em>corpus</em>&mdash;underwent a gradual eclipse in post-Avicennian
Arabic philosophy, this was not due to a decline of its prestige, but
to the success of Avicenna&rsquo;s incorporation of the text and the
doctrine of Aristotle&rsquo;s work in his new encyclopedia of the
philosophical sciences, <em>The Cure or Healing
(Al-&Scaron;if&#257;&#702;</em>) where he constantly stresses his
reliance on the teaching of the &ldquo;First Master&rdquo; (Aristotle)
and his disciples.</p>

<p>
Schematically, Arabic authors adopted three main ways of approaching
the text of Aristotle&rsquo;s <em>Metaphysics</em>, corresponding to
three different literary genres. The first approach, which can be
called &ldquo;taxonomical&rdquo;, is found in classificatory essays
whose goal is to outline the content of the <em>Metaphysics</em> and
to clarify its place in the Aristotelian <em>corpus</em>, as well as
to indicate the position of the discipline of metaphysics in the
system of knowledge. The &ldquo;exegetical&rdquo; approach is
represented by commentaries that aim at explaining, with different
degrees of literalness and comprehensiveness, the content of the
<em>Metaphysics</em>. The tendency to adaptation, finally, is visible
in metaphysical treatises that reformulate the doctrine of
Aristotle&rsquo;s work and are intended as original elaborations,
regardless of the degree of dependence on their Greek model. All main
Arabic metaphysicians approached the <em>Metaphysics</em> from at
least one of these various perspectives.</p>

<p>
From the doctrinal point of view, Arabic interpreters of the
<em>Metaphysics</em> debated three basic theoretical issues. First of
all, they reflected on the scientific configuration of the discipline
presented by Aristotle&rsquo;s work, with special focus on fundamental
aspects such as its subject-matter (namely the issue of whether
metaphysics is a philosophical theology, or an ontology, or both),
structure, method, and position in the system of knowledge. This
consideration of the epistemic status of metaphysics took into account
an enlarged Aristotelian <em>corpus</em>, which included within
theoretical philosophy a mathematics based on Euclid and Ptolemy
(since Aristotle himself wrote no treatise on mathematics), and
complemented the <em>Metaphysics</em> with pseudo-Aristotelian
Neoplatonic metaphysical works (the Plotinian <em>Theologia
Aristotelis</em> and the Proclean <em>Liber de causis</em>). The
second concern is the investigation of specific doctrines related to
the distinct issues dealt with in the <em>Metaphysics</em>. The
prominent topics within the study of being <em>qua</em> being, or
ontology, are the various aspects of the theory of essence, like the
clarification of its relationship with form and substance, the
discussion of the epistemological and ontological status of
universals, etc. Conversely, the debate about the eternity vs. the
origination of the world, and the mode of the universe&rsquo;s
production by the First Principle, whether by way of emanation from
Its own essence or creation <em>ex nihilo</em>, is of central
importance in philosophical theology; likewise, the features that
Aristotle ascribes to the divine Unmoved Mover, with particular regard
to Its unity, necessity and intellectual nature, provide the
starting-points for far-reaching developments. The third concern is
the discussion of the relationship of the philosophical theology
contained in Aristotle&rsquo;s <em>Metaphysics</em> with Islam, namely
the assessment of the degree of compatibility between the rational
conception of the divinity upheld by Greek philosophy, on the one
hand, and the image of God conveyed by Islamic prophetic revelation,
on the other. The assumption of the oneness of truth, common among
Arabic philosophers, allows metaphysics to provide a rational and
coherent account of the same divine realm disclosed by revelation,
thereby putting it in competition with Islamic theology. The results
of these three doctrinal concerns are interconnected, since a certain
view of metaphysics as a science, and a certain stand on specific
doctrinal points, can enhance or reduce the affinity of metaphysics
with Islamic religion and the possibility of its integration into
Muslim culture. A conception of metaphysics that limits its scope to
philosophical theology and minimizes the relevance of ontological
concerns is particularly apt to underscore its compatibility with
Islam. By contrast, a view of metaphysics in which the ontological
dimension plays a role as prominent as the one assigned to
philosophical theology, and in which the First Principle&rsquo;s
properties are discordant, rather than congruent, with the Islamic
divine attributes, goes in the opposite direction.</p>

<p>
The different textual approaches and theoretical solutions to the
aforementioned problems are assumed here as guidelines for the
articulation of the history of the Arabic reception of the
<em>Metaphysics</em>. On this basis, seven main chronological periods
can be roughly distinguished: the first five phases culminate in the
sixth, i.e., in Avicenna, who emerges as the turning point of the
history of Arabic metaphysics.</p>

<h2 id="ArabTranMeta">2. The Arabic Translations of the <em>Metaphysics</em></h2>

<p>
The translation activity regarding the <em>Metaphysics</em> continued
uninterruptedly for three centuries (the ninth to the eleventh), with
the production of several Arabic versions of Aristotle&rsquo;s text,
some of which might have depended on Syriac intermediaries, and the
involvement of a number of different translators, belonging to the
main schools of Arabic philosophy. These translations display
different degrees of inclusiveness (from integral versions of
Aristotle&rsquo;s work to translations of its single books) and
literalness (from strict word for word procedures to styles more akin
to paraphrase). Cumulatively, the Arabic translations of the
<em>Metaphysics</em> evidence the intention of making the entire text
of Aristotle&rsquo;s work accessible to Arabic readers, extending the
translation activity from the first translated main bulk of the work
(books Alpha Elatton-Mu, II&ndash;XIII) towards more peripheral books,
like Alpha Meizon (I) and Nu (XIV). Equally clear is the effort to
provide an Arabic version which, while remaining faithful to the Greek
original, could be more respondent to philosophical clarity, with a
special focus on the repeatedly translated book Lambda (XII). Also
remarkable is the translation of the main available Greek commentaries
on the <em>Metaphysics</em>, namely those of Alexander of Aphrodisias
and Themistius (less certain is the case of Syrianus&rsquo;
commentary), whose explanations of book Lambda (and, in the case of
Syrianus, Beta (III)) were translated together with the corresponding
books of Aristotle&rsquo;s work. Since other Greek works intimately
related to Aristotle&rsquo;s <em>Metaphysics</em> were also translated
into Arabic&mdash;like Theophrastus&rsquo;s <em>On First
Principles</em>, the metaphysical section of Nicholas of
Damascus&rsquo;s <em>On the Philosophy of Aristotle</em>, Alexander of
Aphrodisias&rsquo;s <em>On the Principles of the Universe</em>, the
<em>De aeternitate mundi contra Aristotelem</em> and other
cosmological writings of Philoponus&mdash;the entire Greek exegetical
tradition of the <em>Metaphysics</em>, from Aristotle&rsquo;s first
disciples (Theophrastus) to his last interpreters/reformers
(Philoponus), was available to Arabic-speaking scholars.</p>

<p>
On account of its long duration, the high rank of the scholars it
engaged, and the number of translations produced, this area of the
overall translation movement from Greek into Arabic should not be
reduced to a mere preliminary phase of the Arabic reception of the
<em>Metaphysics</em>, but rather provides a specimen of the main
trends that characterized the first centuries of its history.</p>

<h2 id="AlKindHisScho">3. Al-Kind&#299; and His School</h2>

<p>
Al-Kind&#299; (d. after 870) engaged in a taxonomic approach to
Aristotle&rsquo;s <em>corpus</em>, on the basis of a number of
unidentified Greek sources of Neoplatonic heritage (<em>Treatise on
the Quantity of Aristotle&rsquo;s Books and What is Required to Attain
Philosophy</em>, <em>Ris&#257;la f&#299; kammiyyat kutub
Aris&#7789;&#257;&#7789;&#257;l&#299;s wa-m&#257; yu&#7717;ta&#487;u
ilayhi f&#299; ta&#7717;&#7779;&#299;l al-falsafa</em>). In this
treatise, he expresses an ambivalent view of the place of the
<em>Metaphysics</em> in the <em>corpus</em>, by presenting
Aristotle&rsquo;s work as the culmination of a four-fold division of
philosophy into mathematics, logic, physics, and metaphysics, but also
as preliminary to the knowledge of ethics. The description of the
content of the <em>Metaphysics</em> is limited to the part of this
work dealing with philosophical theology (the study of immaterial
things), and contains explicit references to Islamic tenets such as
God&rsquo;s oneness, the divine names, and providence.</p>

<p>
Due to the loss of what might have been a specific commentary on the
<em>Metaphysics</em> (attested under the title of <em>Inclusive
Philosophy, Falsafa d&#257;&#7723;ila</em>), the exegetical tendencies
of al-Kind&#299; can only be guessed. His extant works on metaphysics
indicate the adoption of the paraphrase as explanatory technique, and
a special attention to book Alpha Elatton (II)&mdash;the first book of
the <em>Metaphysics</em> in the Arabic tradition&mdash;intended as
introductory to the theological themes of book Lambda.</p>

<p>
Al-Kind&#299;&rsquo;s main metaphysical treatise (<em>Book on First
Philosophy</em>, <em>Kit&#257;b f&#299; l-falsafa
al-&#363;l&#257;</em>, only partially extant) displays monotheistic
concerns (the insistence on God&rsquo;s unity, with recourse to a
model of the God-world relationship reminiscent of the Neoplatonic
metaphysics of <em>Theologia Aristotelis</em> and <em>Liber de
causis</em>), and the adoption of the doctrine of the creation of the
universe in time (derived from Philoponus). The explicit encomiastic
references to Aristotle occurring at the beginning of the work (with
extensive paraphrastic excerpts of <em>Metaphysics</em> Alpha Elatton)
and the abrupt switch to the themes of Book Lambda (albeit treated in
an un-Aristotelian vein) confirm that the one-sided theologizing
approach to the <em>Metaphysics</em> is directed at showing the
compatibility of Greek metaphysics with Islamic religion. Thus,
al-Kind&#299; often portrays philosophy in general, and metaphysics in
particular, as the discipline deputed to give full articulation and
rational explanation to the miraculous conciseness of the prophetic
message (besides the central section of <em>On the Quantity of
Aristotle&rsquo;s Books</em>, see also the <em>Epistle on the
Explanation of the Prosternation of the Extreme Body and its Obedience
to God, Ris&#257;la f&#299; l-Ib&#257;na &#703;an su&#487;&#363;d
al-&#487;irm al-aq&#7779;&#257; wa-&#7789;&#257;&#703;atih&#299;
li-ll&#257;hi</em>).</p>

<p>
The view of metaphysics as essentially a science of the divine being,
rather than of being in general, and the intent of underscoring its
affinity, once assimilated with philosophical theology, with Islam,
was also characteristic of al-Kind&#299;&rsquo;s direct disciples and
the &ldquo;school&rdquo; of authors inspired by his teaching or
dependent on his same sources. This is evident both in classifications
of the sciences (Qus&#7789;&#257; ibn L&#363;q&#257;, d. 912; Ibn
Far&#299;&#289;&#363;n, 10th century, the <em>Ras&#257;&#702;il</em>
of the I&#7723;w&#257;n al-&#7778;af&#257;&#702;, written around
961&ndash;986; Miskawayh, d. 1030), and in independent treatises
related to metaphysics (see Ab&#363; Sulaym&#257;n
al-Man&#7789;iq&#299; al-Si&#487;ist&#257;n&#299;, d. ca. 985, and his
school; Ab&#363; l-&#7716;asan Mu&#7717;ammad ibn Y&#363;suf
al-&#703;&#256;mir&#299;, d. 992; Miskawayh).</p>

<h2 id="AabiIbnQurr">4. &#7790;&#257;bit ibn Qurra</h2>

<p>
According to historical sources, &#7790;&#257;bit ibn Qurra (d. 901)
might have revised the translation into Arabic of Themistius&rsquo;
paraphrase of <em>Metaphysics</em> Lambda. More importantly, this
author wrote the first known extant Arabic commentary on the
<em>Metaphysics</em>, still glossed by Ibn Taymiyya (d. 1328) four
centuries later, according to the method of concise exposition
(<em>tal&#7723;&#299;&#7779;</em>), i.e., isolating the most relevant
points of the commented text. This commentary shares with
al-Kind&#299;&rsquo;s works a special regard for philosophical
theology within metaphysics, since it focuses on book Lambda of
Aristotle&rsquo;s <em>Metaphysics</em>. Also Kindian is the effort to
accommodate Islamic monotheism, by insisting on the oneness and
willful action of God, and by adopting the Porphyrian theme of the
harmony between Aristotle&rsquo;s and Plato&rsquo;s teaching. At
variance with al-Kind&#299;, by contrast, is &#7790;&#257;bit&rsquo;s
endorsing of the doctrine of the eternity of the world, rather than
its creation in time, against Philoponus, and the minimal reliance on
Neoplatonic writings. The background of the commentary is decidedly
Aristotelian, with some possible influence of the Peripatetic
commentators (most notably Themistius, who however is never
mentioned); nonetheless, &#7790;&#257;bit revises some crucial tenets
of Aristotle&rsquo;s philosophical theology, by understanding, for
example, the First Mover as the first cause not only of the motion of
the universe, but also of its existence.</p>

<h2 id="AlFaar">5. Al-F&#257;r&#257;b&#299;</h2>

<p>
Besides more traditional overviews of the works of Aristotle and the
place of the <em>Metaphysics</em> among them (<em>What Ought to be
Premised to the Learning of Aristotle&rsquo;s Philosophy, M&#257;
yanba&#289;&#299; an yuqaddama qabla ta&#703;allum falsafat
Ari&#7779;&#7789;&#363;</em>; <em>Aristotle&rsquo;s Philosophy and Its
Parts, Falsafat Aris&#7789;&#363;&#7789;&#257;l&#299;s
wa-a&#487;z&#257;&#702; falsafatih&#299;</em>),
al-F&#257;r&#257;b&#299; (d. 950) also provided taxonomic accounts in
which the <em>Metaphysics</em> is related to the system of the
philosophical and Islamic sciences, rather than to the Aristotelian
<em>corpus</em> of writings. In the most important and influential
essay of this type, the <em>Enumeration of the Sciences</em>
(<em>I&#7717;&#7779;&#257;&#702; al-&#703;ul&#363;m</em>), he portrays
metaphysics as a discipline having a precise method (demonstration)
and an articulated structure, in which a full-fledged ontology (the
study of being <em>qua</em> being) in its different aspects precedes,
first, a part dealing with the foundation of the other sciences and,
second, a philosophical theology concerned, among other things, with
Islamic issues such as God&rsquo;s attributes, and divine names and
actions. In all these classificatory treatises, the position of the
<em>Metaphysics</em> with respect to the other works of Aristotle, or
of metaphysics with respect to the other philosophical disciplines, is
not stable, but varies according to the particular perspective that
al-F&#257;r&#257;b&#299; adopts: significantly, in some of them
metaphysics is presented as the culmination of the entire system of
knowledge, for example, in <em>The Philosophy of Aristotle</em>.</p>

<p>
The consideration of the entire <em>Metaphysics</em>, and the view of
metaphysics as universal science, are the pivotal elements of the
short introduction to the <em>Metaphysics</em> written by
al-F&#257;r&#257;b&#299;, following the model of the Prolegomena of
Greek Late Antiquity and the teaching of Ammonius Son of Hermeias and
his Aristotelian school in Alexandria. This essay, <em>On the Goals of
the Sage</em> [= Aristotle] <em>in Each Treatise of the Book Labelled
by Means of Letters</em> [= <em>Metaphysics</em>] (<em>Maq&#257;la
&hellip; f&#299; A&#289;r&#257;&#7693; al-&#7717;ak&#299;m f&#299;
kull maq&#257;la min al-kit&#257;b al-maws&#363;m
bi-l-&#7717;ur&#363;f</em>), represents the first integral exegesis of
the <em>Metaphysics</em> extant in Arabic and reveals
al-F&#257;r&#257;b&#299;&rsquo;s dependence on the epistemology of the
newly translated <em>Posterior Analytics</em>.
F&#257;r&#257;b&#299;&rsquo;s use of a style of exegesis stemming from
the Peripatetic tradition is evidence of his closeness to the coeval
school of Baghdad Aristotelians. The main point of the work is that
metaphysics is more encompassing than, and not reducible to, the
philosophical theology of book Lambda. Accordingly,
al-F&#257;r&#257;b&#299; first rejects the attempts to interpret
Aristotle&rsquo;s work along Neoplatonic and monotheistic lines (in
this he has probably in mind al-Kind&#299;&rsquo;s theologizing
conception of metaphysics), and advocates a type of explanation akin
to that of the Greek commentators (Alexander of Aphrodisias and
Themistius). Then he derives from the universal nature of metaphysics,
understood as the science having being <em>qua</em> being as its
subject-matter, indications regarding its scope (it incorporates a
part on philosophical theology, namely on the doctrine of the first
causes of being), as well as its oneness (there cannot be more than
one universal science), its name (by being more general than physics
it is also &ldquo;after&rdquo; physics) and its overall content.
Finally, he concludes the work with a brief description of each of the
books of Aristotle&rsquo;s work known to him, in which the content of
book Lambda is summarized with no religious overtones. In this way,
al-F&#257;r&#257;b&#299; extracts from Aristotle&rsquo;s work a
coherent and all-encompassing outline of an &ldquo;ideal&rdquo;
science of metaphysics; this project will guide the following
generations of Arabic metaphysicians, in particular Avicenna, to build
a new science of metaphysics according to Farabian parameters.</p>

<p>
In al-F&#257;r&#257;b&#299;&rsquo;s main works on political
philosophy, philosophical theology is the only part of metaphysics
that functions as preliminary&mdash;together with human noetics,
man&rsquo;s destiny in the afterlife, and prophecy&mdash;to the
account of the organization of the ideal state (<em>Principles of the
Opinions of the Inhabitants of the Virtuous City, Mab&#257;di&#702;
&#256;r&#257;&#702; Ahl al-Mad&#299;na al-F&#257;&#7693;ila</em>).
Other works of his, on the other hand, deal specifically with
ontological themes. Among them, the <em>Book of Letters</em>
(<em>Kit&#257;b al-&#7716;ur&#363;f</em>, which is not, properly
speaking, a commentary on the <em>Metaphysics</em>, despite the title
echoing one of the Arabic names of Aristotle&rsquo;s work) follows a
pattern analogous to that of Book Delta (V) of the
<em>Metaphysics</em>; the treatise <em>On One and Unity</em>
(<em>F&#299; l-w&#257;&#7717;id wa-l-wa&#7717;da</em>) is thematically
linked to Book Iota (X); the refutation of Philoponus&rsquo; criticism
of Aristotle is a reassessment of the thesis of the eternity of the
world. Scattered references to the <em>Metaphysics</em>, with regard
to distinct topics, surface also in the <em>Book on the Agreement of
the Opinions of the Two Sages, the Divine Plato and Aristotle</em>
(<em>Kit&#257;b al-&#486;am&#703; bayna ra&#702;yay
al-&#7717;ak&#299;mayn Afl&#257;&#7789;&#363;n al-il&#257;h&#299;
wa-Aris&#7789;&#363;&#7789;&#257;l&#299;s</em>), a work revolving
around the Porphyrian theme of the harmony between Aristotle&rsquo;s
and Plato&rsquo;s views. This motive had been taken up by
al-Kind&#299; and &#7790;&#257;bit ibn Qurra, but seems alien to
F&#257;r&#257;b&#299;&rsquo;s conception of the history of philosophy.
For this and other reasons, the Farabian authorship of this treatise,
despite the manuscript evidence, has been repeatedly questioned in
recent scholarship.</p>

<p>
The view that metaphysics is the universal science of being
<em>qua</em> being, and thus exceeds the boundaries of philosophical
theology by including it as one of its parts, functions in
al-F&#257;r&#257;b&#299; to underscore the irreducibility of
metaphysics to Islamic religion: at the level of content, metaphysics
ranges over a thematic spectrum wider than the Muslim creed; on
epistemic grounds, the demonstrative method of metaphysics (and of
philosophy in general) is superior not only to the rhetorical and
poetical character of prophetic discourse, but also to the dialectical
procedures of Islamic theology (<em>kal&#257;m</em>). This helps to
explain why al-F&#257;r&#257;b&#299; does not indulge in the
philosophical explanation of the <em>Qur&#702;&#257;n</em>, and why in
the political works does he treat topics pertinent to religion from a
strictly philosophical point of view, with no concession to religious
terminology or theological preoccupations.</p>

<h2 id="BaghAris">6. The Baghdad Aristotelians</h2>

<p>
The <em>Metaphysics</em> held an undisputable importance for the
school of Christian Aristotelians that flourished in Baghdad during
the X&ndash;XI centuries, who took over from the Aristotelian scholars
of Alexandria the project of providing a systematic commentary on
Aristotle&rsquo;s works. Many members of this school&mdash;starting
from its founder, Ab&#363; Bi&scaron;r Matt&#257; ibn Y&#363;nus (d.
940), through to its later leader, Ab&#363; Zakariy&#257;&#702;
Ya&#7717;y&#257; ibn &#703;Ad&#299; (d. 974), and to one of its last
representatives, &#703;&#298;s&#257; ibn Zur&#703;a (d.
1008)&mdash;contributed decisively to the translation of the
<em>Metaphysics</em> into Arabic. Moreover, some of these authors are
credited with the translation into Arabic of parts of the main Greek
commentaries on the <em>Metaphysics</em> (Alexander of Aphrodisias and
Themistius on book Lambda, by Ab&#363; Bi&scaron;r Matt&#257;), or
they were reported to be familiar with the Arabic translation of
further Greek commentaries on Aristotle&rsquo;s work, as well as with
treatises on metaphysics by some of Aristotle&rsquo;s immediate
disciples (for example, Ya&#7717;y&#257; ibn &#703;Ad&#299; was said
to be familiar with the commentary on book Beta by Syrianus and the
original treatise on metaphysics by Theophrastus of Eresus). Finally,
numerous literal commentaries on the <em>Metaphysics</em>, following
in the footsteps of Alexander of Aphrodisias&rsquo; exegetical style,
were produced within this school. Thus, later sources inform us that
Ab&#363; Bi&scaron;r Matt&#257; commented on books Alpha Elatton,
&Beta;eta (III) and Theta (VIII) of the <em>Metaphysics</em>; he is
also quoted in Avicenna&rsquo;s exegesis of book Lambda in the extant
fragments of the <em>Book of the Fair Judgement.</em> Ya&#7717;y&#257;
ibn &#703;Ad&#299;&rsquo;s commentary on book Alpha Elatton is extant.
Ab&#363; l-Fara&#487; ibn al-&#7788;ayyib&rsquo;s (d. 1043) commentary
on the <em>Metaphysics</em>, preserved in fragments in Hebrew
translation, is famous for its length and its attention to every
detail, an exegetical style decidedly resented by Avicenna.</p>

<p>
Ya&#7717;y&#257; ibn &#703;Ad&#299; is the Aristotelian of Baghdad
whose metaphysical orientations are best known, within a corpus of
writings whose boundaries are progressively widened by scholarship.
The literal style of exegesis he deploys in commenting on
<em>Metaphysics</em> Alpha Elatton does not prevent him from
introducing religious concerns into this commentary. The broadly
speaking &ldquo;Platonic&rdquo; theories of some of his treatises
devoted to ontological issues, like the postulation of divine forms
within the discussion of the mode of existence of universals, can be
seen as Platonizing solutions to Aristotelian problems, rather than as
indications of affiliation to non-Aristotelian philosophical
traditions.</p>

<h2 id="IbnSiinAvic">7. Ibn S&#299;n&#257; (Avicenna)</h2>

<p>
Outlines of metaphysics, of various lengths, can be found in
Avicenna&rsquo;s treatises on the classifications of the sciences, as
well as in the surveys of the different branches of philosophy
interspersed in many of his other works. These epistemological
sketches are substantiated in his <em>summae</em>, a literary genre of
which he can be considered the inventor. In all these
&ldquo;encyclopedias&rdquo; of philosophy&mdash;addressed to different
audiences and displaying various formats, methodologies, and
styles&mdash;metaphysics constitutes, together with logic and natural
philosophy, a permanent and pivotal part of philosophy. In those
written in Arabic, after the propaedeutic treatment of logic, the
sequence of theoretical disciplines is given&mdash;along traditional
lines&mdash;as natural philosophy, mathematics, and metaphysics, or
simply as natural philosophy and metaphysics, with mathematics
frequently omitted. By contrast, in the Persian <em>summa, Philosophy
for &#703;Al&#257;&#702; al-Dawla</em>
(<em>D&#257;ni&scaron;n&#257;mah-yi &#703;Al&#257;&#702;&#299;</em>),
and possibly also in the incompletely extant <em>The Easterners</em>
(<em>Al-Ma&scaron;riqiyy&#363;n</em>) or <em>Eastern Philosophy</em>
(<em>Al-&#7716;ikma al-ma&scaron;riqiyya</em>), the order is reversed
and, as Avicenna himself avows, much more original: metaphysics
constitutes the beginning, rather than the end, of theoretical
philosophy. These two opposite arrangements are in fact compatible and
underscore complementary aspects of the primacy of metaphysics within
theoretical philosophy: metaphysics is last in the order of learning
as the pinnacle of philosophical instruction, while it is first in the
order of reality on account of the supreme rank of the things it deals
with.</p>

<p>
In Avicenna&rsquo;s literal commentaries on the philosophical
<em>corpus</em>, most of which are lost, metaphysics represents the
section about which we are best informed by either Avicenna himself or
his disciples (e.g., <em>The Available and the Valid,
Al-&#7716;&#257;&#7779;il wa-l-ma&#7717;&#7779;&#363;l</em>), or by
the surviving portions (e.g., <em>Book of the Fair Judgment,
Kit&#257;b al-In&#7779;&#257;f</em>). Judging from the extant
fragments, conciseness and selectiveness appear to have been the
stylistic and methodological hallmarks of Avicenna&rsquo;s exegesis of
the <em>Metaphysics</em>.</p>

<p>
Avicenna&rsquo;s unprecedented account of the <em>Metaphysics</em> can
be best appreciated in the metaphysical sections of his
<em>summae</em> of philosophy, which sum up the approaches to
Aristotle&rsquo;s work deployed by previous interpreters, namely the
taxonomical reflection on the place of metaphysics in the architecture
of knowledge, the exegetical effort of explaining the
<em>Metaphysics</em>&rsquo; text, and the intent of updating and
upgrading Aristotle&rsquo;s metaphysical model (see
 <a href="#FundTextApprIssu">section 1</a>).
 On the one hand, in so far as they are collections of the different
branches of philosophy, and expound metaphysics together with logic,
natural philosophy, and mathematics, these works give metaphysics a
precise position in the system of the philosophical disciplines. On
the other hand, they provide an explanation of Aristotle&rsquo;s text
by incorporating it into Avicenna&rsquo;s own discourse by means of a
report which modifies the formulation of the original text and changes
the arrangement of its parts. More importantly, they adapt the
scientific profile and the specific content of the
<em>Metaphysics</em> to new epistemological requirements, to the
doctrinal progress of post-Aristotelian philosophy, and to the Islamic
setting with which metaphysics is now called to interact.
Specifically, they adjust the tentative scientific configuration
assigned to <em>Metaphysics</em> by Aristotle himself to higher
epistemological standards; they refine the doctrine of the
<em>Metaphysics</em> and mold it with theories taken from other
authors and works within the Aristotelian tradition, or from the
fruits of Avicenna&rsquo;s own mind; and they make the final treatment
of philosophical theology in metaphysics compliant with religious
concerns and the theological agenda of the Islamic milieu in which
Avicenna&rsquo;s <em>summae</em> are produced.</p>

<p>
Among Avicenna&rsquo;s <em>summae</em>, the most extensive,
influential, and, by the author&rsquo;s own admission, the most
dependent upon Aristotelian sources is the <em>Book of the
Cure/Healing</em> (<em>Kit&#257;b al-&Scaron;if&#257;&#702;</em>). The
&ldquo;traditional&rdquo; character of the work, far from preventing
originality, allows the reader to observe more keenly the
author&rsquo;s subtle and wide-ranging adaptation of the Aristotelian
model and his free disposal of the received material. This applies to
metaphysics in an eminent way. The metaphysical section of the
<em>Cure/Healing, The Science of Divine Things</em>
(<em>Il&#257;hiyy&#257;t</em>), comes at the end of a massive work
consisting in a collection of twenty-two volumes, which is unique
among Avicenna&rsquo;s <em>summae</em> not only with regard to length
(more than 5000 pages in the current printing of the Arabic text, one
of the longest works ever written in the history of philosophy) and
dissemination (the present census of manuscripts surpasses 300) but
also because it is the only <em>summa</em> that contains both a
full-fledged part on mathematics before metaphysics, and a summary
treatment of practical philosophy (politics, economics, and ethics) as
an appendix to metaphysics. In this way, only in <em>The Science of
Divine Things</em>, does metaphysics figure as a real cornerstone of
the entire philosophical curriculum, both with respect to what
precedes (logic and the other two parts of theoretical philosophy) and
with respect to what follows (practical philosophy). More than one
recension of the work turns out to have existed, and Avicenna&rsquo;s
circle of disciples and cooperators probably took part in framing the
version of the text most widely transmitted.</p>

<p>
As to the text of the <em>Metaphysics</em>, in <em>The Science of
Divine Things</em> Avicenna uses several Arabic translations of
Aristotle&rsquo;s work, and adopts various techniques for quoting it:
his way of referring to the <em>Metaphysics</em> is usually very
selective in content and free in style, although in a few cases his
quotations become continuous and resemble a real paraphrase. This
latter case happens with <em>Metaphysics</em> &alpha;, 2, which
Avicenna cites in its entirety, with explicative expansions, in the
eighth treatise of the work, introducing into the paraphrase frequent
references to the <em>Metaphysics</em> (&ldquo;First Teaching&rdquo;)
and its author (&ldquo;First Teacher&rdquo;), as well as an explicit
mention of book Alpha Elatton itself, and defending the doctrines at
stake by offering solutions to a series of possible objections. Within
the ninth treatise, the same special treatment is given, to a lesser
degree, to <em>Metaph.</em> &Lambda;, 6&ndash;10. These excerpts of
Aristotle&rsquo;s text might be fragments of Avicenna&rsquo;s own
previous exegetical works.</p>

<p>
The liberty with which Avicenna reports the text of the
<em>Metaphysics</em> is paramount to his effort of adapting it to a
new context. With respect to Aristoteles&rsquo; work, <em>The Science
of Divine Things</em> exhibits three radical aspects of modification.
Avicenna changes, first of all, the &ldquo;form&rdquo;, i.e., the
scientific profile, of Aristotle&rsquo;s work. Accordingly, he also
modifies its &ldquo;content&rdquo;, namely the disposition and
doctrinal purport of the individual treatises of the work. These two
modifications are concomitant with a third, more general, change,
regarding the position and role of the science of metaphysics in the
system of the sciences. The change regarding the &ldquo;form&rdquo;
affects all the fundamental aspects of a science singled out by
Aristotle in the <em>Posterior Analytics</em>: the theme of
metaphysics, its structure, and its method. The content of the
<em>Metaphysics</em>, on the other hand, is reworked by means of a
different arrangement of its parts, the integration of
Aristotle&rsquo;s thought with subsequent metaphysical speculation,
both Greek and Arabic, the introduction of some original key
doctrines, and a treatment of the divine realm very attentive to the
concerns of Islamic religion and theology. The change regarding the
systemic function of metaphysics, finally, involves a precise view of
its relationship with the other sciences as both foundational and
crowning discipline, thus overcoming Aristotle&rsquo;s veto in the
<em>Posterior Analytics</em> on the subalternation under a single
science of all other disciplines. Cumulatively, in these three ways
Avicenna performs a thorough and radical revision of the authoritative
text on metaphysics, which can be rightly regarded as a sort of second
&ldquo;edition&rdquo; of the <em>Metaphysics</em>, in a dialectical
relationship of both continuity and innovation with respect to
Aristotle&rsquo;s teaching.</p>

<p>
In the context of the epistemological reshaping of the metaphysics,
Avicenna shows first that the subject-matter of this science conforms
to all the different characteristics that Aristotle assigns to it in
the <em>Metaphysics</em>. Thus, metaphysics is a study of the First
Causes and God (cf. <em>Metaph.</em> &Alpha;, 1, 981b28&ndash;29;
&Alpha;, 2, 982b9&ndash;10), since the First Causes and God are its
&ldquo;goal&rdquo;. But it is also a study of &ldquo;the
existent&rdquo; (cf. <em>Metaph.</em> &Gamma;, 1, 1003a20&ndash;26),
since &ldquo;the existent <em>qua</em> existent&rdquo; is its
subject-matter. Finally, metaphysics is a study of immaterial and
unmoved things (cf. <em>Metaph.</em> &Epsilon;, 1, 1026a13&ndash;23),
since both the First Causes and God, and &ldquo;the existent
<em>qua</em> existent&rdquo; are realities of this kind. This
harmonization of Aristotle&rsquo;s different points of view aims at
conforming metaphysics to the epistemological canons of the
<em>Posterior Analytics</em>. Avicenna is the first thinker in the
history of philosophy to have devoted a distinct and articulated
treatment to the issue of the subject-matter of metaphysics, along the
<em>Posterior Analytics</em>&rsquo; insistence on the subject-matter
as the fundamental element of every science. The later impact of
Avicenna&rsquo;s treatment of this topic on Arabic and Latin
philosophy has been enormous, insofar as it settled the issue of how
metaphysics can be both an ontology and a philosophical theology. The
other aspects of the scientific reform of metaphysics introduced by
Avicenna are also the result of applying the epistemological
requirements of the <em>Posterior Analytics</em> to this discipline.
In this way, Avicenna bestows on metaphysics an articulated and
coherent structure, based on the main elements that the <em>Posterior
Analytics</em> spell out as fundamental to every science: the parts,
properties, and principles of its subject-matter, and a method that
is, as much as possible, demonstrative, in keeping with the
<em>Posterior Analytics</em>&rsquo; claim that demonstration is the
most perfect type of proof.</p>

<p>
As to the recasting of the content of the <em>Metaphysics</em>,
Avicenna quotes all the fourteen books into which the
<em>Metaphysics</em> is traditionally divided (apart, perhaps, from
book &Kappa;), but according to an order that is strikingly different
from that of Aristotle&rsquo;s work. This modification allows the
integration of themes taken from other sources, either from other
Aristotelian writings, or from the Greek and Arabic Peripatetic
tradition in which Aristotle&rsquo;s <em>Metaphysics</em> was
commented, elaborated, and expanded, or from Avicenna&rsquo;s own
cultural context. In this last respect, the philosophical theology of
<em>The Science of Divine Things</em> includes a series of themes
familiar to Avicenna&rsquo;s Muslim audience (the existence of God,
His attributes, providence, theodicy, the human soul&rsquo;s destiny
in the afterlife, prophecy etc.), which are treated on a strictly
philosophical basis, but with occasional recourse to examples,
terminology, and scriptural quotations of Islamic provenance, used to
confirm the rational conclusions reached. This, together with the
theological views debated throughout the work, indicates
Avicenna&rsquo;s intention to show that the philosophical world-view
expressed in metaphysics is not contrary or alien to the Islamic one,
and that it can provide rational access to some of the tenets of the
Muslim creed. <em>The Science of Divine Things</em>, however, is not
the mere sum of its many sources. Some of the original doctrines that
Avicenna introduces within the framework of metaphysics run through
the work and serve to connect and unify its various themes. Most
notorious among them are the distinction between essence and existence
in created beings, which is the theoretical leitmotif of the work, and
the metaphysical proof of God&rsquo;s existence, grounded in
Avicenna&rsquo;s view of the subject-matter of metaphysics and of
causation, and representing the pivotal element of the section on
philosophical theology. The distinction between essence and existence
underlies many themes of Avicenna&rsquo;s metaphysics: it justifies,
for instance, the difference between the primary concepts
&ldquo;thing&rdquo; (i.e., &ldquo;that which has an essence&rdquo;)
and &ldquo;existent&rdquo; at the beginning of the work; it grounds
the theory of universals (universality is an attribute that belongs to
an essence not as such, but when this latter exists in the human mind,
abstracted from the extra-mental things in which it is instantiated);
and it leads to the fundamental characterization of God as the only
being that has no essence apart from existence, or whose essence is
totally identical to its existence. Equally important in <em>The
Science of Divine Things</em> is the proof of God&rsquo;s existence,
which is announced at the beginning of the work (I.6) and given
towards its end (VIII.1&ndash;3). It involves a precise view of the
relationship between metaphysics and natural philosophy, in as much as
it is a properly metaphysical argument, independent from the
conclusions reached in physics; it turns out to be original with
regard to the other metaphysical writings of Avicenna, because it is
based not only on a precise doctrine of the <em>Metaphysics</em> (the
finiteness of causal chains in <em>Metaph.</em> &alpha;, 2), but also
on the text itself of this chapter of Aristotle&rsquo;s work, as we
have seen.</p>

<p>
As to the role of metaphysics among the sciences, <em>The Science of
Divine Things</em> grants this discipline a position of eminence with
respect to all other branches of philosophy. The series of parts
constituting the <em>&Scaron;if&#257;&#702;</em> amounts to a concrete
classification of the sciences: in it, metaphysics functions as the
&ldquo;queen of the sciences&rdquo; that ascertains the principles
taken for granted by all the other sciences, and interconnects and
orders hierarchically the system. Metaphysics is foundational insofar
as it is the universal science of the existent <em>qua</em> existent
(ontology). The scientific principles assessed by metaphysics are, on
the one hand, the logical laws common to all the sciences (the
axioms), and the universal concepts that every science uses without
examining them (the primary concepts like &ldquo;existent&rdquo;,
&ldquo;thing&rdquo;, &ldquo;necessary&rdquo;, &ldquo;one&rdquo;). On
the other hand, metaphysics clarifies the principles that are proper
to each of the particular sciences, i.e., their specific assumptions
or hypotheses. Thus, metaphysics proves the very existence and the
mode of existence of the subject-matters of the other theoretical
sciences (for example, the existence of universals and categories in
logic, of matter and form in natural philosophy, and of discrete and
continuous quantity in mathematics). In as much as it clarifies the
existential underpinnings of the phenomenon of prophecy, after the
functional presentation of prophecy provided in psychology,
metaphysics turns out to be foundational also with respect to the
ensuing practical philosophy (X.4&ndash;5), of which the doctrine of
prophecy represents the leitmotif.</p>

<p>
In Avicenna, all the previous trends of the Arabic tradition of the
<em>Metaphysics</em> converge and find their synthesis. This is
particularly manifest in the philosophical theology that invariably
concludes his accounts of metaphysics in the <em>summae</em> and that
finds its most lucid expression in <em>The Science of Divine
Things</em>. In this section, on the one hand Avicenna reiterates the
connection between <em>Metaph.</em> &alpha;, 2 and &Lambda;,
6&ndash;10 that was typical of al-Kind&#299;&rsquo;s selective way of
approaching the <em>Metaphysics</em>; on the other hand, he
incorporates procedures of explanation <em>ad litteram</em> and by way
of questions (<em>per modum quaestionis</em>) of Aristotle&rsquo;s
text (with particular regard to <em>Metaph.</em> &alpha;, 2) that are
reminiscent of the Baghdad Aristotelians&rsquo; exegetical method; in
a third respect, he discusses a sequence of themes that mirrors the
structure of the theological philosophy of
al-F&#257;r&#257;b&#299;&rsquo;s political treatises. The Aristotelian
core of this section is expanded by means of accretions taken from
Alexander of Aphrodisias&rsquo; and Themistius&rsquo; works on
metaphysics (the Aristotelian commentators mentioned by
al-F&#257;r&#257;b&#299; and translated into Arabic by the Baghdad
Aristotelians), and from the pseudo-Aristotelian, Neoplatonic works
that were commonly appended to the <em>Metaphysics</em> in Arabic
philosophy, i.e., the Plotinian <em>Theologia Aristotelis</em> and the
Proclean <em>Liber de Causis</em>, produced within
al-Kind&#299;&rsquo;s circle. As a result, Avicenna&rsquo;s
metaphysics harmonizes al-Kind&#299;&rsquo;s emphasis on the
theological component of the <em>Metaphysics</em> with
al-F&#257;r&#257;b&#299;&rsquo;s vindication of the foundational role
of ontology; by the same token, he reconciles
al-F&#257;r&#257;b&#299;&rsquo;s view of metaphysics as a science
modeled on the epistemology of the <em>Posterior Analytics</em> with
the Baghdad Aristotelians&rsquo; project of a global explanation of
Aristotle&rsquo;s text. In this way, the congruence of metaphysics
with Islamic theology is not realized in a &ldquo;Kindian&rdquo; way,
i.e., by limiting the scope of this discipline to a part of the
<em>Metaphysics</em>, but depends, in a more &ldquo;Farabian&rdquo;
vein, upon the entire work of Aristotle once its inner structure and
its goal has been properly underscored.</p>

<p>
The other metaphysical <em>summae</em> by Avicenna single out and
emphasize particular aspects of the overarching architecture of
metaphysics displayed in <em>The Science of Divine Things</em>. Thus,
<em>The Book of Pointers and Reminders</em> (<em>Kit&#257;b
al-I&scaron;&#257;r&#257;t wa-l-Tanb&#299;h&#257;t</em>) underscores
the importance of philosophical theology within metaphysics by
expanding it with respect to a much thinner ontology; the Persian
<em>The Book of Science for &#703;Al&#257;&#702;-al-Dawla</em>
(<em>D&#257;ne&scaron;n&#257;me-ye &#703;Al&#257;&#702;&#299;</em>)
places metaphysics as the first theoretical discipline (before natural
philosophy and mathematics), after the preliminary logic, in order to
signal its priority in the system of the sciences; the lost
metaphysics of <em>The Easterners</em>
(<em>Al-Ma&scaron;riqiyy&#363;n</em>) or <em>The Eastern
Philosophy</em> (<em>Al-&#7716;ikma al-ma&scaron;riqiyya</em>) might
have formalized the divide between ontology and philosophical theology
within metaphysics by splitting metaphysics into two distinct sciences
corresponding to these two parts. The metaphysics of <em>The Book of
Salvation</em> (<em>Kit&#257;b al-Na&#487;&#257;t</em>), finally,
though structurally similar to <em>The Science of Divine Things</em>,
differs from it in specific points and formulations (most notably, in
how the proof of God&rsquo;s existence is structured), in so far as it
incorporates doctrines from Avicenna&rsquo;s previous metaphysical
works.</p>

<p>
Besides the overall treatment of metaphysics in the <em>summae</em>,
Avicenna investigates particular metaphysical areas in specific
treatises, such as the <em>Book of Provenance and Destination</em>
(<em>Kit&#257;b al-Mabda&#702; wa-l-ma&#703;&#257;d</em>), which
focuses, within metaphysics, on philosophical theology, or the
<em>Epistle of Immolation about Destination</em> (<em>Al-Ris&#257;la
al-a&#7693;&#7717;awiyya f&#299; amr al-ma&#703;&#257;d</em>), which
concentrates on a specific topic of philosophical theology, i.e. the
return of the human soul after death, separated from the body, to its
place of origin, or in allegorical writings, such as the
<em>&#7716;ayy ibn Yaq&#7827;&#257;n</em> or the <em>Epistle of the
Bird</em> (<em>Ris&#257;lat al-&#7788;ayr</em>). Various issues
pertaining to metaphysics are extensively debated in works that
contain Avicenna&rsquo;s reflections on key philosophical themes, such
as the <em>Notes</em> (<em>Ta&#703;l&#299;q&#257;t</em>), or that
derive from the teaching activity and the dialectical practices
performed within his circle, i.e., the <em>Discussions</em>
(<em>Mub&#257;&#7717;a&#7791;&#257;t</em>). Related to metaphysics are
the specific essays ascribed to Avicenna and devoted to the
philosophical and allegorical interpretation of some Qur&rsquo;anic
verses, whose authenticity however remains to be assessed.</p>

<h2 id="PostAvicPeri">8. Post-Avicennian Period</h2>

<p>
The three approaches to Aristotle&rsquo;s <em>Metaphysics</em>
considered here (classification, commentary, adaptation), as well as
the main schools of thought of the formative period (the Kindian, on
the one hand, and the Farabian-Baghdadian, on the other), ended or
began to wither with the rise of Avicenna&rsquo;s metaphysics.
Although the text of Aristotle&rsquo;s <em>Metaphysics</em> continued
to circulate in Arabic after the eleventh century, the metaphysical
works of Avicenna gradually superseded the <em>Metaphysics</em> as the
text to be copied, commented upon, and evaluated (either favorably or
critically). Accordingly, in the post-Avicennian metaphysical
tradition issues specifically regarding Avicenna&rsquo;s metaphysics
are debated, like the status of essence and existence and the primacy
of the one over the other, or whether a philosophical theology
modelled on Avicenna is more entitled than Islamic dialectical
theology, or <em>kal&#257;m</em>, to be the discipline deputed to
speak about God.</p>

<p>
The reception of Avicenna&rsquo;s metaphysics in subsequent Arabic
thought is multifaceted, and detailed work in this immense area has
only begun in recent decades. Previous scholarship has established the
following landmarks:</p>

<p>
First, a clear distinction between the direct vs. the indirect
influence of Avicenna&rsquo;s metaphysics, i.e., between those who
actually consulted his works, and those whose knowledge depended on
earlier readers of Avicenna. A case of the latter way of transmission
are the two very influential text-books of Qur&#702;&#257;nic schools
(madrasas), A&#7791;&#299;r al-D&#299;n al-Abhar&#299;&rsquo;s (d.
660H/1262 or 663H/1265) <em>Hid&#257;yat al-&#7717;ikma</em>, and
Na&#487;m al-D&#299;n al-K&#257;tib&#299; al-Qazw&#299;n&#299; (d.
1276) <em>&#7716;ikmat al-&#703;ayn</em>, whose metaphysical sections
are largely dependent on Avicenna and decisively contributed to its
dissemination.</p>

<p>
Second, three main attitudes towards Avicenna&rsquo;s metaphysics in
post-Avicennian Arabic philosophy can tentatively be outlined:
acceptance, revision, and rejection. A decidedly favorable setting is
represented by a network of scholars, along at least three generations
of Avicenna&rsquo;s school members, who explicitly connected
themselves with the master&rsquo;s teaching. Significantly, some of
the most direct disciples of Avicenna, like Ab&#363;
l-&#703;Abb&#257;s Fa&#7693;l ibn Mu&#7717;ammad al-Lawkar&#299;
(V&ndash;VI/XI&ndash;XII c.), are the models to which later heirs of
Avicenna&rsquo;s metaphysics ideally refer (see, for instance,
&#288;iy&#257;&#7791; al-D&#299;n Man&#7779;&#363;r ibn Mu&#7717;ammad
&#7716;usayn&#299; Da&scaron;tak&#299; &Scaron;&#299;r&#257;z&#299;,
d. 948H/1542).</p>

<p>
On the opposite side, a &ldquo;conservative&rdquo; reaction to
Avicenna&rsquo;s metaphysics (and to Avicenna&rsquo;s philosophy in
general) was represented by the efforts of reinstating the
pre-Avicennian status of this discipline. This goal was pursued in
various ways. Some, like &Scaron;ih&#257;badd&#299;n
al-Suhraward&#299; (d. 1191) and the fabricators of Arabic
Pseudo-Platonica in the twelfth century, took Pythagoras&rsquo; and
Plato&rsquo;s thought as true philosophy, thus supplanting the
Aristotelian tradition to which Avicenna belonged. Others, like Ibn
Rushd/Averroes (d. 1198), whose three commentaries on the
<em>Metaphysics</em> contain recurrent criticisms of Avicenna,
redirected attention to Aristotle&rsquo;s <em>Metaphysics</em> itself,
with the aim of restoring the original purport of Aristotle&rsquo;s
foundational text against Avicenna&rsquo;s innovations. Still others,
such as &#703;Abd al-La&#7789;&#299;f al-Ba&#289;d&#257;d&#299; (d.
1231), conceived metaphysics as a mere juxtaposition of the Kindian
and Farabian perspectives on metaphysics, thus resolving the
Avicennian synthesis into its constituents. In addition to these
anachronistic attempts that surface both in the East and in the West
of the Muslim world and are advanced by philosophers in the strict
sense, there were also the attacks launched against philosophy in
general, and metaphysics in particular, by Muslim theologians, most
famously by Ab&#363; &#7716;&#257;mid al-&#288;az&#257;l&#299; (d.
1111) in <em>The Incoherence of the Philosophers</em>
(<em>Tah&#257;fut al-Fal&#257;sifa</em>). Significantly, however, all
the critics of Avicenna, regardless whether philosophers or
theologians, are also indebted to his thought, and in their eyes
Avicenna&rsquo;s metaphysics represents metaphysics <em>tout
court</em>.</p>

<p>
A further intermediate line of influence, which is the one that
ultimately prevails, is the fruitful and positive
&ldquo;contamination&rdquo; of Avicenna&rsquo;s metaphysics with
systems of thought originally foreign to it. This happened, for
example, with regard to the theory of illumination (Mu&#7717;ammad ibn
Ma&#7717;m&#363;d al-&Scaron;ahraz&#363;r&#299;, 2<sup>nd</sup> half
of the VII/XIIIc.), or to sufism (Mu&#7717;y&#299;&#702; al-D&#299;n
ibn &#703;Arab&#299;, d. 1240; Ibn Sab&#703;&#299;n of Murcia, c.
1217&ndash;1270; &#7778;adr al-D&#299;n al Q&#363;naw&#299;,
1207&ndash;1274). But the most noteworthy aspect of this
tendency&mdash;which possibly starts in the cultural environment where
al-&#288;az&#257;l&#299; was formed&mdash;is the adoption of
Avicenna&rsquo;s metaphysics by Muslim theologians or
<em>mutakallim&#363;n</em>. In general, the tendency to integrate
Avicenna&rsquo;s metaphysics into new doctrinal settings represents
the most interesting area of its reception, since a thorough and solid
grasp of Avicenna&rsquo;s original stance is required to adapt it
properly to an illuminationist, mystical, or theological context.
Together with the trends towards acceptance or rejection, this
tendency to revise stretches over a period which is much longer than
the pre-Avicennian phase of <em>falsafa</em>.</p>

<p>
Third, in a diachronic perspective, within the vast scenario of the
reception of Avicenna&rsquo;s philosophy, after the first main period
of impact already documented in scholarship (from Avicenna&rsquo;s
death until the middle of the VIII/XIV c.), further later significant
phases of influence in different areas of the Islamic world (Persia,
India, Ottoman empire) are emerging. This temporal progression and
geographical expansion involve metaphysics as a prime element.</p>

<p>
A key factor in the evaluation of the later impact of Avicenna&rsquo;s
metaphysics is the assessment of which of his works mainly influenced
later reflections on metaphysics, their ways of transmission, and
their audience, since each of them, as we have seen, conveys a
particular version and format of metaphysics. Among them, the
metaphysical section of the <em>Book of Pointers and Reminders</em>
has been singled out in scholarship because of the proliferation of
independent commentaries on it from the late XII until the early XVIII
century by leading figures of Arabic philosophy like Fa&#7723;r
al-D&#299;n al-R&#257;z&#299; (d. 1209) and Na&#7779;&#299;r
al-D&#299;n al-&#7788;&#363;s&#299; (d. 1274). Scholars attribute the
success of Avicenna&rsquo;s <em>Pointers and Reminders</em> to
doctrinal, stylistic, and chronological factors. Doctrinally,
Avicenna&rsquo;s use of the essence-existence distinction to support
the distinction between the ontological constituents that are
intrinsically necessary (like the essence of something) and those that
are extrinsically necessary (like its existence) was particularly
obvious in the <em>Pointers and Reminders</em>. Stylistically, the
work&rsquo;s limited size and its abbreviated and allusive style
invited elaboration and commentary. Chronologically, this was
Avicenna&rsquo;s final comprehensive work and therefore could be taken
as the definitive expression of his views. For these reasons, the
<em>Pointers and Reminders</em> are currently considered to be the
work of Avicenna privileged by subsequent Muslim philosophers
(including the <em>mutakallim&#363;n</em>).</p>

<p>
<em>The Science of Divine Things</em> also played an important role in
spreading Avicenna&rsquo;s metaphysics among later advocates of this
discipline. This is evident from its extensive manuscript tradition,
the vast exegetical activity devoted to <em>The Cure/Healing</em>, and
the frequent and widespread quotations of <em>The Science of Divine
Things</em> among post-Avicennian authors. Transmitted by a huge
number of manuscripts (more numerous and older than the ones of the
<em>Pointers and Reminders</em> currently known), <em>The Science of
Divine Thing</em> and the other parts of the <em>Cure/Healing</em>
were copied uninterruptedly for nine centuries, from the end of V/XI
century, a few decades after Avicenna&rsquo;s death, until the XIV/XX
century. Its exegetical tradition is first attested in the form of
marginalia, which never circulated independently from manuscripts
before the X/XVI c, when the earliest extant independent commentaries
on the text, in fact collections of marginal glosses in self-standing
book format, started to be produced. The
<em>ta&#703;l&#299;q&#257;t</em> of &#288;iy&#257;&#7791; al-D&#299;n
Da&scaron;tak&#299; &Scaron;&#299;r&#257;z&#299; and of
&#7778;adr&#257; al-D&#299;n (Mull&#257; &#7778;adr&#257;)
al-&Scaron;&#299;r&#257;z&#299; (d. 1640) are noteworthy instances of
this trend, at the time of a new-born interest in <em>The
Cure/Healing</em>, and of an apparent loss of interest in the
<em>Pointers and Reminders</em>, whose commentatorial activity begins
to decrease. Later lemmatic commentaries, like the one by
Mu&#7717;ammad Mahd&#299; ibn Ab&#299; &#7694;arr al-Nar&#257;q&#299;
(d. 1794/5), like its ancestors, cover only parts of <em>The Science
of Divine Things</em>, since the work in its entirety&mdash;455 pages
in the current printing&mdash;was too huge to be commented line by
line, and no integral commentary has ever been written on it or on one
of the other twenty-one sections of <em>The Cure/Healing</em>, let
alone on the <em>summa</em> in its entirety. Finally, <em>The Science
of Divine Things</em> is abundantly quoted by a wide array of scholars
and writings, including the commentators on the <em>Pointers and
Reminders</em>, as the reference work to be consulted in case of
theoretical uncertainties or for doctrinal integrations and
developments. The lithographic printing of the <em>The Science of
Divine Things</em> produced at Tehran towards the end of the 19th
century (1885&ndash;1888), where Mull&#257; &#7778;adr&#257;&rsquo;s
commentary precedes Avicenna&rsquo;s text and this latter is glossed
by means of an exorbitant amount of marginalia, provides a vivid
representation of the exegetical accretions that the work underwent
along the centuries.</p>

<p>
In this context, the metaphysical sections of <em>The Book of Science
for &#703;Al&#257;&#702;-al-Dawla</em> and of <em>The Book of
Salvation</em> should also be taken into account. The former work
obtained wide resonance since it was taken as a model and incorporated
by al-&#288;az&#257;l&#299; in his exposition of philosophy (<em>The
Intentions of the philosophers, Maq&#257;&#7779;id
al-Fal&#257;sifa</em>), a conduit for Avicenna&rsquo;s metaphysics in
the West as well. The latter work was copied in manuscripts at a very
ancient stage, and it was commented upon by important scholars like
&#7826;&#257;hir al-Din ibn Funduq al-Bayhaq&#299; (d.
1169&ndash;1170) and Fa&#7723;r al-D&#299;n
al-Isfar&#257;&#702;in&#299; al-N&#299;s&#257;b&#363;r&#299; (fl.
VI/XII c.).</p>

<p>
At the present stage of research, we can tentatively conclude that no
single work of Avicenna conveyed his metaphysical thought to later
centuries, although it is premature to assess how these different
writings interacted or competed in transmitting Avicenna&rsquo;s view
of metaphysics. It is therefore difficult to say which of these works
enjoyed the status of Avicenna&rsquo;s most influential metaphysical
work. In this respect, the wide manuscript diffusion, the intense
commentatorial activity, and the high consideration enjoyed by <em>The
Science of Divine Things</em> deserve special attention: the
transmission process of this work crosses the centuries and represents
an uninterrupted trail of post-Avicennian philosophy, from
Avicenna&rsquo;s first disciples until today, unattested in the case
of the other metaphysical works by Avicenna. In the continuum
represented by the circulation of <em>The Science of Divine
Things</em>, one may discern a peak: this is the Safavid era in Iran
(XVI&ndash;XVIII c.), which&mdash;if it is right to call &ldquo;golden
age&rdquo; of Arabic philosophy the period 1100&ndash;1350&mdash;can
be labelled the &ldquo;platinum&rdquo; age of the reception of
Avicenna&rsquo;s metaphysics. But this peak has firm roots in previous
centuries, especially in the key-figure of Na&#7779;&#299;r
al-D&#299;n al-&#7788;&#363;s&#299; and his school, and extends both
backwards and forwards, in the larger frame of post-Avicennian
<em>falsafa</em>.</p>

<h2 id="Conc">9. Conclusion</h2>

<p>
The study of Arabic metaphysics can be approached from a variety of
interconnected perspectives. On the historical side, one can follow a
group of interrelated trends, such as the way in which the
<em>Metaphysics</em> was transmitted into Arabic and integrated in the
culture of its new environment, how it interacted with the Arabic
reception of other fundamental works of Aristotle (above all the
<em>Posterior Analytics</em>, but also the <em>Categories</em>), and
how it instantiated in Arabic philosophy the main Greek paradigms of
interpretation of the Aristotelian <em>corpus</em> (the Athenian
background of al-Kind&#299;&rsquo;s philosophy vs. the Alexandrian
heritage of the Aristotelians of Baghdad, or the purer Peripatetism of
al-F&#257;r&#257;b&#299; vs. the Platonizing Aristotelianism of
Ya&#7717;y&#257; ibn &#703;Ad&#299; and his followers). On the
theoretical side, the epistemological reflection on metaphysics as a
science undertaken by Arabic philosophers, in the effort to transform
Aristotle&rsquo;s still imperfect discipline into a full-fledged and
rigorous scientific discourse, redirects attention from the
<em>Metaphysics</em> (with capital &ldquo;M&rdquo;) to metaphysics
(with lower-case &ldquo;m&rdquo;). More generally, outside the
narrower scope of the history and the epistemic evolution of
metaphysics, it is interesting to observe how the introduction of a
foreign pagan discipline, like metaphysics, into a monotheistic social
context, like the Islamic one, determined either the harmony or the
antagonism between philosophical theology and revealed theology, or,
in other words, between the quintessence of <em>falsafa</em>, on the
one hand, and the speculation of <em>kal&#257;m</em>, on the other.
The study of the ways in which this confrontation took place in the
Islamic culture of the Middle Ages may shed light on the contemporary
debate on the relationship between reason and faith and contribute to
the promotion of a moderate version of Islam and of dialogue and
tolerance among distinct religions.</p>
</div>

